deck: Mysterious individual who purports to have helped teach Superman in his early years and is currently watching him for unknown reasons.
description:
Creation

Mr. Oz was created by comic book writer Geoff Johns and artist John Romita Jr., first appearing in issue 32 of Superman (vol. 3). However, he remained nameless until issue 35, when his name was spoken by the villain known as the Machinist.

Story Arcs

Superman: The Men of Tomorrow

Mr. Oz makes several appearances throughout the story arc but never steps in during the events of the story. Instead, he is seen monitoring the adventures of Superman and Ulysses from an unknown location via television monitors. Mr. Oz calls Superman by his actual name, Clark Kent, and talks about Superman as if he knows him personally, claiming to have taught him to always get up when he gets knocked down and that Superman always has to be alone. At one point, it is shown that he is not necessarily talking only to himself, but that there is someone else with him, locked away in a vault-like room next to him. To this person is never seen, however.

During his battle with Superman, the Machinist reveals himself to be in league with Mr. Oz in some fashion, claiming that Mr. Oz told him that the world will always want weapons and that Superman would never be rid of him. The only other person to have had contact with Mr. Oz is a woman named Miss Janet, who delivered a package from Mr. Oz to Clark Kent at the Daily Planet. Janet sported a "Oz" tattoo on her wrist, showing that she is most likely some kind of employee. The package, when Clark opens it, is revealed to be a blank, black notebook, bearing the "S" shield on the cover.

DC Universe Rebirth

Mr. Oz appears again in the DC Universe Rebirth one-shot, set immediately after the events leading to Superman's death. Mr. Oz visits the pre-New 52 Superman, living under the false name White, when he steps away from his family, pre-New 52 Lois Lane and their son Jonathan. Mr. Oz shows knowledge of this Superman's life as well, remarking how fast Jonathan is growing up. When confronted by Superman, Mr. Oz claims to be neither friend or foe, but rather as a messenger. He tells Superman that he and his family are not what they believe they are and neither was the New 52 Superman. Before the conversation could continue, Mr. Oz disappears right in front of Superman.

description:
Origin

Nothing is known about Venna's origin. They are presumably the hereditary ruler of Dark Earth, though they may have taken the throne by force. They died along with all of their subjects, bar Nimraa, when Dark Earth was destroyed by the arrival of light.

Creation

Venna was created by JM DeMatteis and Yvel Guichet. They made their first appearance in Trinity of Sin #5.

Major Story Arcs

The Wages of Sin

Venna and their people are brought back into being by a ritual performed by Nimraa. However, Nimraa's work is so well done that Venna and the members of their court are unaware of ever having been dead. They are dismissive of Nimraa and Nimraa's continual insistence of her part in bringing Dark Earth back. They attack Nimraa and break the Redemption Box, endowing the Trinity of Sin with its powers. They are destroyed when the Trinity absorbs the Dark Earth.

Powers and Abilities

Venna is a three-headed being, and each head appears to be its own individual person. They are superhumanly strong.

Weapons and Equipment

Venna carries a large sword with three prongs.
